De pgausu] It seems 35 if Cicero ad- mitted that there was not much applause, that Caesar in fact was looked on as a usurper‚ or was not popular. The reason that Cicero gives for there being no ap- plause is a piece of the meanest and silliest flattery that ever came from a man, even from him. It is in the style of the adula- tion paid to James I., whom Bacon places above Caesar and M. Antoninus “in all literature and erudition, divine and human.”

But Cicero made amends by what he said of Caesar after his death (Phil. ii. c. 32) and elsewhere.
